{"title_page": "Embrace of the Serpent", "text_new": "{{short description|2015 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Embrace of the Serpent\n| image          = Embrace_of_the_Serpent_poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Ciro Guerra]]\n| producer       = Cristina Gallego\n| writer         = Ciro Guerra<br>Jacques Toulemonde Vidal\n| based on       = [[Theodor Koch-Grunberg]] and [[Richard Evans Schultes]] (diaries)\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n*Jan Bijvoet\n*Nilbio Torres\n*Antonio Bol\u00edvar}}\n| music          = Nascuy Linares\n| cinematography = David Gallego\n\n| editing        = Etienne Boussac\n| distributor    = Diaphana Films\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n*Buffalo Films\n*Buffalo Producciones\n*[[Caracol Televisi\u00f3n]]\n*Ciudad Lunar Producciones\n*Dago Garc\u00eda Producciones\n*MC Producciones\n*Nortesur Producciones\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|5|15|[[2015 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2015|5|21|Colombia|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |title=En mayo, cosecha de estrenos colombianos en la pantalla grande |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/CMS-15714955 |newspaper=[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]] |language=Spanish |date=8 May 2015 |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n| runtime        = 125 minutes\n| country        = Colombia<br />Venezuela<br />Argentina\n| language       = [[Cubeo language|Cubeo]]<br>[[Witoto languages|Huitoto]]<br>[[Ticuna language|Ticuna]]<br>[[Wanano language|Wanano]]<br>Spanish<br>Portuguese<br>German<br>Catalan<br>Latin<br>English\n| budget         = $1.4 million<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/CMS-16480834 |title='Este es el momento del cine colombiano': Ciro Guerra |newspaper=El Tiempo |language=Spanish |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $3.4 million<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=embraceoftheserpent.htm |title=Embrace of the Serpent (2016) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Embrace of the Serpent''''' ({{lang-es|'''El abrazo de la serpiente'''}}) is a 2015 Colombian [[international co-production|internationally co-produced]] [[adventure film|adventure]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Ciro Guerra]], and written by Guerra and Jacques Toulemonde Vidal. Shot almost entirely in black and white, the film follows two journeys made thirty years apart by the indigenous shaman Karamakate in the Colombian [[Amazon rainforest|Amazonian jungle]], one with Theo, a German ethnographer, and the other with Evan, an American botanist, both of whom are searching for the rare plant ''yakruna''. It was inspired by the travel diaries of [[Theodor Koch-Grunberg]] and [[Richard Evans Schultes]], and dedicated to lost Amazonian cultures.\n\n''Embrace of the Serpent'' was premiered on 15 May 2015 during the [[Directors' Fortnight]] section at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]], where it won the Art Cinema Award. The film was released in Colombia on 21 May 2015, and worldwide over the course of the following twelve months. It has received universal acclaim from critics, who praised the cinematography and the story's impact of the destruction of the Amazon rainforest and way of life by white colonialism. It has won numerous awards, including the [[Alfred P. Sloan Prize]] at the 2016 [[Sundance Film Festival]], the Grand Jury Prize for Best Picture at the 2017 [[Riviera International Film Festival]], and seven awards at the [[3rd Platino Awards]] to recognise the best Ibero-American films of 2015, including the [[Platino Award for Best Ibero-American Film]]. In 2016 the film was submitted as Colombia's entry for the category of [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[88th Academy Awards]] and was included among the final five nominees, becoming the first Colombian film ever to receive a nomination for an Academy Award.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film tells two stories thirty years apart, both featuring Karamakate, an Amazonian [[shaman]] and last survivor of his tribe. He travels with two scientists, firstly with the German Theo von Martius in 1909 and then with an American named Evan in 1940, to look for the rare ''[[Psychotria viridis|yakruna]]'', a sacred plant.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jordan |last=Hoffman |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/feb/17/embrace-of-the-serpent-review-ciro-guerra-colombian-amazon |title=Embrace of the Serpent review \u2013 dreamlike exploration of the Amazon's imperialist pollution |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 February 2016 |accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nTheo, an ethnographer from [[T\u00fcbingen]] who has already been residing in the Amazon for several years, is very sick and is travelling by canoe with his field notes and a westernised local named Manduca whom he had saved from enslavement on a rubber plantation. Karamakate prolongs his life, blasting white powder called \"the sun's semen\" (possibly a hallucinogenic made from [[virola]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Christina |last=Pratt |title=An Encyclopedia of Shamanism \u2013 Volume 2: N\u2013Z |publisher=[[Rosen Publishing|Rosen Publishing Group]] |page=423 |date=1 June 2007 |isbn=978-1-40421-141-4}}</ref>) up his nose, but is reluctant to become involved with a westerner and refuses his money. Theo is searching for yakruna as the only cure for his disease and the three set off in the canoe to search for it.\n\nMany years later an American botanist, Evan (Brionne Davis), paddles up to a much older Karamakate (Antonio Bol\u00edvar) who has apparently forgotten the customs of his own people. Evan says he is hoping to complete Theo's quest and Karamakate does assist, again reluctantly, saying his knowledge is spent. Evan has a book of Theo's final trek, which his aide had sent back to Europe, as he did not survive the jungle. The book includes an image of Karamakate, which he refers to as his [[chullachaqui]], a native term for hollow spirit. Karamakate agrees to help him only when Evan describes himself as someone who has devoted himself to plants, although Evan's real purpose is actually to secure disease-free [[Hevea brasiliensis|rubber tree]]s, since the United States's supplies of rubber from South East Asia had dwindled due to the Japanese wartime advance.\n\nBoth expeditions feature a Spanish Catholic Mission by the side of an Amazon tributary, run in 1909 by a sadistic, lone Spanish priest who beats orphan boys for any \"pagan\" behaviour, and in 1940 by a delusional [[Brazilian people|Brazilian]] figure who believes he is the Messiah. He only trusts the visitors when he believes they are the [[Biblical Magi]], but Karamakate wins his respect when he heals his wife. By now the children of 1909 have grown into disturbed and violent acolytes.\n\nIn 1909, we are left with Theo, sick and having fled the Mission, arriving at a frontier post just about to be invaded by Colombian soldiers during the [[Amazon rubber boom]], where the sacred yakruna is being abused by drunken men, and cultivated, against local traditions. Karamakate is furious and destroys it. In 1940, Karamakate does show Evan the origin of the plant in striking denuded dome-shaped mountains ([[Cerros de Mavecure]]), allegedly the home of yakruna. He reveals one yakruna flower that is on the last plant \u2013 he has destroyed all the others \u2013 and prepares it for Evan. The preparation being hallucinogenic, aids Evan in undergoing a superconscious experience. While most of the film is in black-and-white, a part of this experience is shown in colour to signify its intensity. The film ends with a transformed Evan remaining enamoured by a group of butterflies.\n\n== Cast ==\nIn ''[[Cineaste (magazine)|Cineaste]]'' magazine, the film's writer and director [[Ciro Guerra]] noted how the process of finding an actor who can successfully communicate the film's narrative was considered to be a difficult task. After his attempt in reaching out to a variety of indigenous people, it had come to his attention that the older generation were completely detached from the time depicted within the film. Through watching a film over 10 years ago in a workshop with the [[Ministry of Culture (Colombia)|Ministry of Culture]], Guerra was able to find the perfect actor, Nilbio Torres. Torres's two minute presence in the short film had a great impact on Guerra, encouraging him to pursue appointing him the role of Karamakate as \"There was nobody else that could play this guy. He's one of the last Ocaina people remaining. There's only about sixteen of them left.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Michael |last=Guill\u00e9n |url=https://www.cineaste.com/spring2016/embrace-of-the-serpent-ciro-guerra |title=Embrace of the Serpent: An Interview with Ciro Guerra |magazine=[[Cineaste (magazine)|Cineaste]] |volume=41 |number=2 |date=Spring 2016 |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe chemistry between the two explorers was undoubtedly a perfect fit for the film. [[Richard Evans Schultes]] was an admired figure by many, he also had an eerie side to him that Guerra wanted to delve further into. Therefore, by pairing him with [[Brionne Davis]], it highlighted the parallels between the two characters. The two actors spent a lot of time with another during the production of the film  the relationship between the two strengthened greatly. Davis's virtuous presentation is made use of and then subverted as a means of playing with the audience's emotions and trust, a key feature prevalent throughout the film.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nThe cast are as follows:\n\n*Nilbio Torres as Young Karamakate\n*Antonio Bol\u00edvar as Old Karamakate\n*Jan Bijvoet as Theo\n*[[Brionne Davis]] as Evan\n*Luigi Sciamanna as Gaspar\n*Yauenk\u00fc Migue as Manduca\n*Nicol\u00e1s Cancino as Anizetto\n\n== Themes ==\nThe film explores the representation of the first people nations of the Amazon. In the film multiple languages are spoken: [[Ocaina language|Ocaina]] (which is most frequently spoken), [[Ticuna language|Ticuna]], [[Bora language|Bora]], [[Andoque language|Andoque]], [[Yucuna language|Yucuna]] (Jukuna), and [[Muinane language|Muinane]].{{citation needed|date=February 2019}} The indigenous peoples are shown to have suffered at the hands of colonizers, and Colombian film critic and author Pedro Adri\u00e1n Zuluaga states that Guerra highlights this by \"shooting peripheric geographies... and bring to the centre of the narrative an unavoidable contradiction between progress and tradition\".<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Pedro Adri\u00e1n |last1=Zuluaga |first2=Gabriella |last2=Munoz |url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2018/latin-american-cinema-today/contemporary-colombian-cinema-the-splintered-mirror-of-a-country/ |title=Contemporary Colombian cinema: the splintered mirror of a country |journal=Senses of Cinema |number=89 |date=December 2018 |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> Daniela Berghahn, a professor of film studies at the [[University of London]], notes how through time-lapse, Guerra highlights the pillaging of the Amazon rain forest by conquistadors, missionaries and rubber barons, and also the enslavement and degradation of the indigenous peoples, who were converted to Christianity \u2014 the character Manduca is both enslaved and Westernised \u2014 at the cost of their traditions and beliefs. The black and white cinematography bears similarity to the [[daguerreotype]] photography of early twentieth century explorers who initially documented the Amazon and inspired the film.<ref name=\"Alphaville\" />\n\n== Production ==\nBefore production started, the director spent two and a half years researching the Colombian Amazon. They discovered a part of the jungle in the north west that had not yet been heavily affected by tourism or commerce and after gaining permission from the local community, they decided on the location.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Adam |last=Woodward |url=https://lwlies.com/articles/embrace-of-the-serpent-ciro-guerra-heart-of-darkness/ |title=Tropical malady \u2013 making a film in the heart of darkness |magazine=[[Little White Lies (magazine)|Little White Lies]] |date=8 June 2016 |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> The pre-production and shooting took place over the course of three months with the help of around 40 people from outside the Amazon and 60 people from indigenous communities within the Amazon. The director extensively collaborated with the community and invited them to participate and collaborate both in front and behind the camera. To avoid any problems caused by the harsh environment, the indigenous people taught the crew how to work with the jungle and performed rituals for spiritual protection. Because of this, there were no accidents or illnesses and the shooting ran smoothly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/wd7k74/embrace-of-the-serpent-is-a-violent-psychedelic-film-about-the-colonization-of-the-amazon|title='Embrace of the Serpent' Is a Violent, Psychedelic, Film About the Colonisation of the Amazon|last=Salas|first=Camilo|date=8 January 2016|website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref> Additionally, Guerra let the indigenous people translate the script, during which they redrafted parts to make it more accurate.<ref name=\"Alphaville\">{{cite journal |last=Berghahn |first=Daniela |title=Encounters with Cultural Difference: Cosmopolitanism and Exoticism in ''Tanna'' (Martin Butler and Bentley Dean, 2015) and ''Embrace of the Serpent'' (Ciro Guerra, 2015) |url=http://www.alphavillejournal.com/Issue14/ArticleBerghahn.pdf |journal=Alphaville: Journal of Film and Screen Media |number=14 |pages=16\u201340 |date=Winter 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cerros de Mavecure (Guain\u00eda, Colombia).JPG|thumb|Cerro Mono and Cerro Pajarito, in the [[Cerros de Mavecure|Mavicure Hills]], which feature in the film.]]\n''Embrace of the Serpent'' was filmed in the [[Amazon natural region|Amazon\u00eda region]] of Colombia. Seven weeks were spent filming in the [[Vaup\u00e9s Department|Department of Vaup\u00e9s]], and one week in the [[Guain\u00eda Department|Department of Guain\u00eda]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Ramos |first=Nick |title=EXCLUSIVE: Embrace of the Serpent Star on Making Film |url=https://morementum.tv/embrace-of-the-serpent-morementum-entertainment-2/ |website=MoreMentum |date=9 May 2016|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> Location details include:\n*[[Cerros de Mavecure|Cerros de Mavicure]] \u2013 three mounds that form part of the westernmost part of the [[Guiana Shield]] in northern South America.\n*Fluvial Star In\u00edrida \u2013 a [[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar Wetland]] that includes part of the [[In\u00edrida River]].\n*[[Vaup\u00e9s River]] \u2013 tributary of the [[Amazon River]] that forms part of the international border between Colombia and Brazil.\n\n=== Crew ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Ciro Guerra]]&nbsp;\u2013 director, screenwriter\n*Jacques Toulemonde&nbsp;\u2013 screenwriter\n*Cristina Gallego&nbsp;\u2013 producer\n*David Gallego&nbsp;\u2013 cinematographer\n*Carlos E. Garc\u00eda&nbsp;\u2013 sound designer, re-recording mixer, additional music composer\n*Ang\u00e9lica Perea &nbsp;\u2013 production designer\n*Catherine Rodriguez&nbsp;\u2013 costume designer\n*Andr\u00e9s Barrientos&nbsp;\u2013 acting coach\n*Etienne Boussac &nbsp;\u2013 editor\n*Nascuy Linares&nbsp;\u2013 music composer\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe soundtrack album of the movie was released by Plaza Major Company on 22 January 2016 and contains nine songs composed by Nascuy Linares.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2016/01/12/embrace-of-the-serpent-soundtrack-announced/ |title='Embrace of the Serpent' Soundtrack Announced |publisher=Film Music Reporter |date=12 January 2016}}</ref> The film also features ''[[The Creation (Haydn)|The Creation]]'' by [[Joseph Haydn]].\n\n=== Track listing ===\n{{tracklist\n| title1          = Embrace of the Serpent (Theme)\n| length1         = 1:59\n| title2          = Trance (Trance Aereo)\n| length2         = 1:59\n| title3          = Dantesque Celebration (Fiesta Dantesca)\n| length3         = 2:29\n| title4          = Acoutic River (Tema Br\u00fajula)\n| length4         = 3:17\n| title5          = [[Gustavo Dudamel|Dudamel]]: Let the Children Play (End)\n| length5         = 1:41\n| title6          = Dudamel: Let the Children Play (Isla y P\u00e1ramo)\n| length6         = 1:44\n| title7          = Dudamel: Let the Children Play \u2013 Sarabande (Based on a Theme by [[George Frideric Handel]])\n| length7         = 2:02\n| title8          = Dudamel: Let the Children Play (Arpegios)\n| length8         = 0:50\n| title9          = Dudamel: Let the Children Play (Minor)\n| length9         = 1:44\n}}\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical response ===\nThe film has received universal acclaim from critics. Review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives it a 96% approval rating, based on 139 reviews, with an average score of 8.3/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"As rich visually as it is thematically, ''Embrace of the Serpent'' offers a feast of the senses for film fans seeking a dose of bracing originality\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Embrace of the Serpent (El Abrazo de la Serpiente) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/embrace_of_the_serpent/ |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalised rating, the film has a score of 82 out of 100 based on 31 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Embrace of the Serpent |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/embrace-of-the-serpent |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[Indiewire]]'''s Jessica Kiang awarded the film an A rating, calling it \"a soulful, strange and stunning discovery\". She also described the character of Karamakate as \"an immaculate portrait of the unfathomable loneliness and crushing survivor's guilt that comes with being the last of one's kind\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Kiang |first=Jessica |title=Cannes Review: 'Embrace Of The Serpent' Is A Soulful, Strange And Stunning Discovery |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2015/05/cannes-review-embrace-of-the-serpent-is-a-soulful-strange-and-stunning-discovery-263927/ |website=[[IndieWire]] |date=17 May 2015 |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> Jordan Mintzer of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' described the film as \"a visually mesmerizing exploration of man, nature and the destructive powers of colonialism\" and compared it to [[Miguel Gomes (director)|Miguel Gomes]]' ''[[Tabu (2012 film)|Tabu]]'' (2012). He also praised the black-and-white cinematography and the sound design which he said \"makes the jungle truly come alive\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Mintzer |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/embrace-serpent-el-abrazo-de-795876 |title='Embrace of the Serpent' ('El abrazo de la serpiente'): Cannes Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=15 May 2015 |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> [[Justin Chang]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave a positive review of the film. He wrote: \"At once blistering and poetic, not just an ethnographic study but also a striking act of cinematic witness...\". About the parallel narrative he wrote it \"delivers a fairly comprehensive critique of the destruction of indigenous cultures at the hands of white invaders\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Justin |last=Chang |authorlink=Justin Chang |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/film-review-the-embrace-of-the-serpent-1201510916/ |title=Film Review: 'Embrace of the Serpent' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=2 June 2015 |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> Will Lawrence of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' awarded the film four stars out of five and said that \"though inspired by real-life journals, Guerra's film transports us into the realm of the mystical and surreal\".<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Will |last=Lawrence |title=Review: Embrace of the Serpent |magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |page=52 |date=July 2016}}</ref> Video essayist [[Kogonada]] voted for the film on ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' magazine's poll for best film of 2015, stating that \"''Embrace of the Serpent'' is a mesmerizing feat of cinema. Guerra had me at frame one.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |author=[[Kogonada]] |title=kogonada {{!}} The best films of 2015 |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/best-films-2015-all-the-votes/#/?poll=combined&voter=2bf75e |magazine=[[Sight & Sound]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |date=27 November 2015 |accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Response from the indigenous community ===\nThe film was well received by the Amazonian community featured in the film. A special screening was held in the jungles of Colombia, in a makeshift cinema. With tribes people from all over the area showing up, not everyone could be seated. After the film finished, they asked for it to be shown again. Although the film was celebrated, director Ciro Guerra did stress that the film should not be used as an attempt to share traditional knowledge of the tribes, as what you see in the film \"is an imagined Amazon because the real Amazon doesn't fit in one film\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jun/08/embrace-of-the-serpent-star-my-tribe-is-nearly-extinct|title=Embrace of the Serpent star: 'My tribe is nearly extinct'|last=Mathiesen|first=Karl|date=8 June 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\nThe film was screened in the [[Directors' Fortnight]] section at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |first=Justin |last=Chang |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/cannes-directors-fortnight-lineup-unveiled-1201476479/ |title=Cannes: Directors' Fortnight Unveils 2015 Lineup |date=21 April 2015 |accessdate=21 April 2015 |work=Variety}}</ref> where it won the Art Cinema Award.<ref>{{cite web |first=Rebecca |last=Ford |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-2015-directors-fortnight-awards-797335 |title=Cannes: 'Embrace of the Serpent' Tops Directors' Fortnight Awards |date=22 May 2015 |accessdate=22 May 2015 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> The film won the Golden Apricot at the 2015 [[Yerevan International Film Festival]], [[Armenia]], for Best Feature Film; the Special Jury Award at the Odessa Film Festival, and the Spondylus Trophy at the Lima Film Festival.\n\nThe Governor of the [[Guain\u00eda Department]] decorated Ciro Guerra with the Order of the In\u00edrida Flower for \"exalting the respect and value of the indigenous populations, likewise giving the Department recognition for tourism and culture\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://guainia.gov.co/index.shtml?apc=I-xx-1-&x=1366487 |title=Sitio web del Departamento de Guain\u00eda |website=guainia.gov.co |language=Spanish |accessdate=24 November 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe film was announced as Colombia's [[List of submissions to the 88th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film|submission]] for the 2016 [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-colombia-selects-embrace-serpent-823925 |title=Oscars: Colombia Selects 'Embrace of the Serpent' for Foreign-Language Category |last=Mango |first=Agustin |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=17 September 2015 |accessdate=17 September 2015}}</ref> and was selected among the final five contenders, being the first Colombian film to be nominated for the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscar-nominations-2016-full-list-855670 |title=Oscar Nominations: The Complete List |work=The Hollywood Reporter |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|- style=\"